COMPETITOR #1: SALESFORCE SALES CLOUD
================================================================================

OVERVIEW
--------
- Market leader with 20%+ CRM market share
- Part of broader Salesforce ecosystem
- Typical pricing: $150-300/user/month (Enterprise editions)
- Strength: Ecosystem, brand recognition, breadth of features

WHEN WE WIN
-----------
✓ Speed of deployment (weeks vs. months)
✓ AI-native forecasting (our core strength)
✓ Lower TCO (40-60% less than comparable Salesforce setup)
✓ Easier administration (no dedicated admin required)
✓ Modern, intuitive UX

WHEN WE LOSE
------------
✗ Customer already invested heavily in Salesforce ecosystem
✗ Need for highly custom workflows (Salesforce's AppExchange)
✗ Risk aversion ("nobody gets fired for buying Salesforce")
✗ Global enterprise with complex multi-org requirements

KEY BATTLEGROUND: FORECASTING
-----------------------------
SALESFORCE: Einstein Forecasting available but requires additional license.
Manual forecasting is painful. Reports are complex to build.

VELOCITYRM: AI forecasting included in Professional+. 85% accuracy vs.
Salesforce's typical 60-70%. Forecasts update automatically, not quarterly.

TALK TRACK:
"Salesforce pioneered CRM, and we respect that. But their forecasting was
bolted on years after the core product. VelocityRM was built AI-first for
forecasting. Our customers consistently achieve 85%+ forecast accuracy -
that's 20-30 points higher than what we see with Salesforce. Would 20% better
forecast accuracy change how you run your business?"

LANDMINES TO SET (questions to plant):
- "Ask Salesforce how many customers achieve >80% forecast accuracy."
- "Ask about total cost including implementation, admin, and add-ons."
- "Ask about their average time-to-value for new customers."

OBJECTION: "We're already on Salesforce"
RESPONSE: "Many of our customers came from Salesforce. They weren't unhappy
with Salesforce overall, but they needed better forecasting and pipeline
intelligence. Some kept Salesforce for other use cases and layered VelocityRM
on top. Would you be open to seeing how that works?"

